lt will be observed that, besides class 3, which related to wbat cannot ever have been a very common case, classes 5, 6, and 8 did not come into consideration unless the intestata were a lreedman or a freedwoman. Class 3 became meaningless under Justinian’s new system ol emancipa- tion, and the other three he altogether abolished. Thus in his legislation intestate bonorum possessores were arranged in four classes only, their order being-liberi, legitimi, cognati, vir et uxor; but he also retained an anomalous group (§8 inl), called sometimes for the sake ol brevity ‘tum quibus ex legibus,’ comprising those persons to whom the statute law had enacted that bonorum possessio (as distinct from the hereditas) should be given: e. g. the patron in concurrence with the children oi a libertus under the lex Papia Poppaea, Tit. 7. 1 and 2 supr: ‘quippe cum non alias huic competit bonorum possessio, quam silex specialiter delerat bonorum possessionem’ Dig. 38. 14. 1. 2.

Fora discussion ol the probable origin oi bonorum possessio, and oi its development into an organized scheme of succession, see Excursus lV, at the end oi tbis Boolc A little more is necessary in order to thoroughly understand its nature.

In order to obtain possession os property belonging to the deceased, the bonorum possessor had, as such, a special procedure, the interdict Quorum bonorum (Dig. 43. 2. 1.—pr., Gaius iv. 144), which had certain advantages over the remedy available to the heres, quoheres (viz. here- ditatis petitio, by which he established his title to the universitas iuris). Thus, the interdict was never excluded by usucapio lucrativa (p. 221 supa: cf. Gaius ii. 52-58), and availed also against persons ‘qui dolo desierant possidere :’ hereditatis petitio was not thus privileged until the time os Hadrian, Dig. 5. 3. 20. 6-21, ib. 25. pr.-r7. lt is then no matter lor surprise that heirs, who had an unimpeachable civil title, applied lor bonorum possessio secundum tabulas in order to be ableto use the interdict, d 1 supr, Gaius iii. 345 and similarly, as the heir could claim to become bonorum possessor, so the praetor treated the bonorum possessor
